<h2>RingConn Gen 2 Air — The budget option ($149)</h2>
<p>If your budget is tight, the RingConn Gen 2 Air offers basic sleep and health tracking at half the price. It doesn't have the accuracy of the above, but as an entry into the world of smart rings it's a valid option.</p>
<h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Why does Oura Ring charge a subscription and others don't?</p><p class="faq-item__a">The business model is different. Oura funds its AI algorithm through the subscription, which is constantly updated. Competitors charge more for hardware and offer the software free with fewer advanced features.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Do no-subscription rings get software updates?</p><p class="faq-item__a">Yes, all release regular app updates. Not as frequent as Oura but basic features improve over time.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">How much do you save over 3 years by choosing no-subscription?</p><p class="faq-item__a">Oura Ring costs $349 + $216 over 3 years subscription = $565. Samsung Galaxy Ring is $299 one-time. The savings over 3 years is $266.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Does Samsung Galaxy Ring work with all Android phones?</p><p class="faq-item__a">It requires Android 11 or higher and Samsung Health installed. It works with any Android, not just Samsung, though integration is deeper with Samsung's own devices.</p></div>
<div class="faq-item"><p class="faq-item__q">Is there a no-subscription ring for iOS as good as the Oura?</p><p class="faq-item__a">The Ultrahuman Ring Air is the closest no-subscription alternative for iOS. It doesn't reach Oura's level in HRV and advanced analysis, but for the average user the difference isn't decisive.</p></div>
